sols:
Before taking derivatives, we will fill in the first table, by testing
values in the two intervals listed.

Note that $x^2 + 1$ will always be positive, so when calculating whether
the function/derivatives are positive or negative, it is sufficient to
look at the numerator as the denominator will always be positive.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $(-\infty, 0)$, test point $x = -1$
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[]
\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
$f(-1) = \frac{-1}{(-1)^2 + 1} = \frac{-1}{2} < 0$
\end{description}
\end{description}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $(0, \infty)$, test point $x = 1$
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[]
\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
$f(1) = \frac{1}{(1)^2 + 1} = \frac{1}{2} > 0$
\end{description}
\end{description}

So the first table should be filled in as:

\begin{longtable}[c]{@{}llll@{}}
& $(-\infty,0)$ & 0 & $(0,\infty)$\\
\emph{$f$(x)} & - & 0 & +\\
\end{longtable}

Proceeding to the second table, we will calculate the first derivative
using the quotient rule:

$f'(x) = \frac{1*(x^2 + 1) - x(2x)}{(x^2 + 1)^2} = \frac{1 - x^2}{(x^2 + 1)^2}$

Setting equal to zero and solving for \emph{x} gives:

$\displaystyle 0 = 1 - x^2$

That is, $\displaystyle x = -1$, $\displaystyle x = 1$. These are then
our values for $c_1$ and $c_2$. We can now test points in the three
intervals labeled in the table.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $(-\infty, -1)$, test point $x = -2$
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[]
\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
$f'(-2) = \frac{1 - (-2)^2}{((-2)^2 + 1)^2} = \frac{-3}{25} < 0$
\end{description}
\end{description}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $(-1,1)$, test point $x = 0$
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[]
\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
$f'(0) = \frac{1 - (0)^2}{((0)^2 + 1)^2} = \frac{1}{1} > 0$
\end{description}
\end{description}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $(1, \infty)$, test point $x = 2$
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[]
\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
$f'(2) = \frac{1 - (2)^2}{((2)^2 + 1)^2} = \frac{-3}{25} < 0$
\end{description}
\end{description}

Filling in the table should look like this:

\begin{longtable}[c]{@{}llllll@{}}
& $(-\infty,c_1)$ & \emph{c\textsubscript{1}} &
$\displaystyle (c_1,c_2)$ & \emph{c\textsubscript{2}} & $(c_2,\infty)$\\
\emph{$f$'(x)} & - & 0 & + & 0 & -\\
\end{longtable}

Finally, we compute the second derivative, again using the quotient
rule:

\begin{align*}
f''(x) &= \frac{-2x(x^2 + 1)^2 - (1-x^2)(2)(x^2 + 1)(2x)}{(x^2 + 1)^4} \\
&= \frac{-2x(x^2 + 1) -(1-x^2)(4x)}{(x^2 + 1)^3} \\
&= \frac{-2x^3 -2x -4x+4x^3}{(x^2 + 1)^3} \\
&= \frac{2x^3 -6x}{(x^2 + 1)^3} \\
&= \frac{2x(x^2-3)}{(x^2 + 1)^3}
\end{align*}

Again solving for where $\displaystyle f''(x) = 0$ we have

$\displaystyle 0 = 2x(x^2 - 3)$

which yields critical points of $x = -\sqrt{3}, x = 0$ and
$x = \sqrt{3}$, which will be $r_1, r_2, r_3$ respectively. When testing
points in each of the four intervals of the table, it is worth noting
that $\sqrt{3}$ is somewhere between 1 and 2.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $(-\infty, -\sqrt{3})$, test point $x = -2$
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[]
\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
$f''(-2) = \frac{2(-2)((-2)^2 -3)}{({-2}^2 + 1)^3} = \frac{-4}{5^3} < 0$
\end{description}
\end{description}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $(-\sqrt{3}, 0)$, test point $x = -1$
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[]
\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
$f''(-1) = \frac{2(-1)((-1)^2 - 3)}{({-1}^2 + 1)^3} = \frac{4}{2^3} > 0$
\end{description}
\end{description}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $(0, \sqrt{3})$, test point $x = 1$
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[]
\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
$f''(1) = \frac{2(1)((1)^2 -3)}{({1}^2 + 1)^3} = \frac{-4}{2^3} < 0$
\end{description}
\end{description}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  $(\sqrt{3}, \infty,)$, test point $x = 2$
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[]
\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
$f''(2) = \frac{2(2)((2)^2 -3)}{({2}^2 + 1)^3} = \frac{4}{5^3} > 0$
\end{description}
\end{description}

Filling in the table yields:

\begin{longtable}[c]{@{}llllllll@{}}
& $(-\infty,r_1)$ & \emph{r\textsubscript{1}} &
$\displaystyle (r_1,r_2)$ & \emph{r\textsubscript{2}} &
$\displaystyle (r_2,r_3)$ & \emph{r\textsubscript{3}} & $(r_3,\infty)$\\
\emph{$f$}(x)'' & - & 0 & + & 0 & - & 0 & +\\
\end{longtable}
